Wakefield COVID protocols for tonight & Saturday's VB games:

Due to the ongoing COVID-19 pandemic, the following protocols will be enforced while inside Wakefield High School.
Capacity: Our main gym capacity is 899. With current recommendations of 50% from the DHM, our full capacity will be 450. Our activity center gym capacity is 267. With current recommendations of 50%, our full capacity will be 134. Once full capacity is reached, we will deny fans.
Fans must wear masks.

Spectators are encouraged to self-screen before traveling to the game, wear face coverings &/or social distance themselves.

Congratulations to the BRLD Men’s Cross Country Team for winning the Championship plaque at the Wisner-Pilger Invitational with a team score of 56 points! Nineteen schools were represented at the meet. Individual medalists include Caleb Schlichting, 7th; Micah Henschen, 12th; and Zach Hegge 13th.

Nebraska School Activities Association
August 17 at 9:02 AM ·

NSAA Membership Monday: Bancroft-Rosalie Community Schools

Home of the Panthers, Bancroft-Rosalie is located in District 3 and offers three activities and co-ops with Lyons-Decatur Northeast (Wolverines) to offer 13 sports. Bancroft-Rosalie Superintendent Dr. Jon Cerny serves as the NSAA District 3 Board of Director. The Panthers have won nine NSAA State Championships in five sports. While co-oped with Lyons-Decatur Northeast, the Wolverines have won two NSAA State Championships in boys basketball.

The County-level risk dials are updated weekly based upon data through the end of the day on Monday (so a Tuesday to Monday week).
· Criteria used to calculate the risk dials weekly include: positivity rate of tests overall, positivity rate of tests over the past few weeks, trajectory of cases over the past few weeks, ICU bed availability, critical medical equipment availability (ventilators, PPE), case clusters vs. general community spread of cases and our capacity to contact trace within 24 hours.

post_text:
Cuming County dial this week is yellow- Moderate risk/community spread.

Explaining the risk dial-
The position of the Risk Dial is based on multiple local indicators and information from the previous three weeks. Below are five of the key factors they consider:

Case numbers. Does the trend shows an increase or decrease in case numbers?

Positivity rate. The average weekly positivity rate for the last three weeks- Is it going increasing or decreasing?

Contact tracing capacity. Is the number of contact tracers available to conduct case investigations sufficient and can keep pace with demand?
Is testing completed and results available in a timely manner or are there delays of the investigative process which impacts the department's ability to prevent the development of case clusters or outbreaks.

Hospital capacity. What is the percent of ICU beds available and ventilators available?

Testing capacity. How many individuals have been tested and how many tests are completed each week?

post_text:
Bancroft-Rosalie Alumni-
Some of you will remember when the old Bancroft building was torn down in 1998 and the new school was being built at that same spot.
We had school without any of the existing new classrooms or gym for a year, using the current elementary and shop classrooms for high school, and the old Rosalie school building for elementary and junior high.

Lunches were cooked in Rosalie and delivered over to Bancroft, high school students were served on the stage.
No locker rooms in the Fall- high school students went home after practice to shower.
For two weeks the shop class had to have class outside until the dry-wall was finished.
Mr. Peters had class in the basement of the old Rosalie school in a room that hadn't been used for over 10 years.

A crazy year.

We made it through.

What do you remember about the wild Fall of 1998?

post_text:
REMOTE LEARNING PARENT/GUARDIAN SURVEY MAY 14-18

Bancroft-Rosalie School will be using the Nebraska Association of School Boards to administer a parent survey on our remote learning program. The school is asking for feedback to understand whether the families in our school district feel informed, supported, and are receiving the necessary resources in order to ensure each child in the district has what he/she needs during this time. Please give your honest opinion.

ABOUT THE SURVEY
Parents/guardians will receive an email and a unique survey link for each child they have enrolled in the district. They will be asked to answer the six (6) question survey based on the experience of each child. NASB will manage the survey and ensure the data collected is private and secure.

The survey will be open from May 14-18. The survey results will be available to the school on May 19 for the staff to discuss what we are doing well and how we can improve remote learning in the future.

post_text:
All remaining NSAA activity practices and competitions, including district and state competitions, have been cancelled for this school year. These cancelations are part of a new Directed Health Measure issued by Governor Ricketts.

Bylaw 3.2.7 (Summer Activities) will go into effect on May 26th. In the interim, Bylaw 3.2.6.1 (School-Year, Out-of-Season) is expected to be followed by all member school athletic programs.

The NSAA continues to encourage all member schools to follow CDC, local, state and federal health department recommendations.

The May 1st Transfer List deadline remains unchanged.

Any further official updates will be posted on the NSAA website and the NSAA social media platforms.

Gov. Pete Ricketts released a directive at 8:45 p.m. Wednesday night that Nebraska schools are to operate without students in their buildings through May 31 and that extracurricular activities have been canceled statewide through May 31 because of the coronavirus pandemic, meaning there will not be a spring sports season in Nebraska high schools.
No clarification yet from the state on how what to do regarding graduations

ATTN FAMILIES CURRENTLY RECEIVING SCHOOL MEALS DURING THE DAY: We are learning daily what is & isn't working, so please bear w/us. To limit ANY physical contact & to keep EVERYONE safe, please refer to the picture below.

Please put some type of box/container by your front door/lane, so that the meals can be placed in the box. FROM NOW ON, deliveries will be made between 11 a.m. & 1 p.m. (or as close as possible b/c every day is different & our numbers are increasing every day).

The driver will honk & leave the meals in your provided container. We will NO LONGER text or call, so it'll be your responsibility to watch for the deliveries.

Thank you! FYI: We sure enjoy seeing those little faces & smiles waving from the windows!!

post_text:
Dr. Cerny received a call this morning from the Elkhorn-Logan Valley Health Department informing him that Bancroft-Rosalie Community School was named in a press release today regarding a presumptive positive test for Coronavirus at the March 5 Girls Basketball State Tournament Game with Crofton.

"It has been determined that exposures may have occurred in the general Crofton fan section."

The Health Department has informed me that no quarantine is needed just because we were in the same arena.

At this time, there have been no changes to the Boys State Basketball Tournament.

As a precaution, if you are ill, stay home. Follow the guidelines for proper hand-washing and other personal hygiene.

If you have any questions, please feel free to contact our school nurse, Linda Munderloh, at 402-648-3336.

post_text:
Congrats to B-R senior Jaxon Johnson, who will be suiting up for the Wildcat football team next fall.

Jaxon Johnson, Defensive End, 6-3, 235 Bancroft, Neb. / BRLD HS

Johnson is a four-year starter in football and three years in basketball for the Wolverines…named Class C-2 All-State during senior season helping BRLD to a 10-2 record and Class C-2 semifinals…on defense recorded 79 tackles with seven sacks and 12 tackles for loss and as a tight end on offense had 787 yards receiving and seven touchdowns…named to Huskerland Class C-2 All-Decade Team and was voted Defensive MVP of the River Battle Bowl…also a standout in basketball earning Class C-2 Second Team All-State honors last season after grabbing 466 rebounds as a junior.

McMenamin about Johnson – “Huge get for the Wildcats. Top player in the area and can play a multitude of positions.”
